nd literal middle. They are Iranian nationals by birth and by choice, and they are Jews by religious affiliation. Full loyalty to their country is expected, even as their ancestral homeland is at odds with their political homeland. This photographic chronicle illuminates the grey zone that they inhabit.Featuring over one hundred full-color photos, contextualized with extensive annotations, and accompanied by a substantive introduction written by historian Lior B. Sternfeld, Jews of Iran calls into question Western views of this religious community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aPhotography / Subjects & Themes / Regional (see also TRAVEL / Pictorials).2bisacsh  aIran Judaism.  aIran religious minorities.  aIran.  aIranian Jews.  aIranian Revolution 1979.  aIranian diaspora.  aIsrael.  aJews in the Middle East.  aMizrahi/Sephardi history.  athe Islamic Republic.1 aSternfeld, Lior B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVahidmanesh, Parvaneh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076692940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271093635?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271093635423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271093635/original  a978-3-11-076692-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK